\details{
\strong{Coefficient interpretation:}
\itemize{
\item \emph{Count component}: exponentiating a coefficient gives the multiplicative
change in the expected Tweedie mean among observations that are not
structural zeros, for a one-unit increase in the predictor.
\item \emph{Zero component}: exponentiating a coefficient gives the multiplicative
change in the odds of being a structural zero (vs. entering the count
process) for a one-unit increase in the predictor. A value greater than 1
means higher odds of a structural zero.
}

\strong{When to use:} Zero-inflated Tweedie is the most flexible model in glmOJ.
It handles excess zeros and complex variance structures simultaneously.
Prefer this over \code{\link[=zeroinflPoissonGLM]{zeroinflPoissonGLM()}} or \code{\link[=zeroinflNegbinGLM]{zeroinflNegbinGLM()}} when count
data show overdispersion and excess zeros that neither of those families
adequately captures. When using \code{\link[=countGLM]{countGLM()}}, this model is fitted only
when the DHARMa zero-inflation test flags the base Tweedie fit
